SPOTTED FEVER, FATAL - BRAZIL (03): (SAO PAULO)
***********************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 29 Jul 2011
Source: EPTV [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.JW, edited]
http://eptv.globo.com/noticias/NOT,1,9,360942,Saude+alerta+sobre+febre+maculosa.aspx


The Health Department of Valinhos is warning people to take care to
prevent spotted fever, a disease that has killed 5 people in the city
in 2011. The dry climate facilitates the proliferation of the tick
that transmits the disease.

Of the 7 confirmed cases in 2011 in Valinhos among the 27 reported, 5
ended fatally. In 2010, of the 38 cases of spotted fever reported, 2
were confirmed and resulted in one death.

Health officials of the Department of Public Health, city of Valinhos,
are advising the public about the risks of spotted fever disease
transmitted by ticks infected with the bacteria _Rickettsia
rickettsii_. Health teams have visited the neighborhoods of Bom
Retiro, Frutal, Parque das Colinas and Capuava, where there are rivers
and lakes, natural habitat of capybaras, host of the tick. The city is
also placing warning signs along the Ribeirao Pinheiro and Bom Jardim
creek, a region where capybaras usually appear.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT via ProMED-mail
