[Brazilian spotted fever is known in Portuguese as "febre maculosa
brasileira". The disease is quite similar to Rocky Mountain spotted
fever, with only subtle differences. The etiological agent,
_Rickettsia rickettsii_, is considered almost identical to its North
American counterpart.

The disease was first described in 1929 but underwent a
still-unexplained disappearance in the 1960s and 1970s. Since 1985, it
has been found with increasing frequency in Sao Paulo and Minas Gerais
states, but cases have also been seen in Rio de Janeiro and Espirito
Santo states. Cases have also been identified in the state of Santa
Catarina in the south. The main vector tick is _Amblyomma cajennense_,
but _A. cooperi_ has been also implicated. - Mod.LL

Valinhos in Sao Paulo state can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil at
http://healthmap.org/r/15Rn. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

[Capybaras (_Hydrochoerus hydrochaeris_) are the world's largest
rodents, and are aquatic -- see photo:
http://blog.rifftrax.com/wp-content/photos/_capybara.jpg - Mod.JW]
